    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a classic sign of a nutrient deficiency, likely nitrogen or iron, which is a common problem for tomato plants, but it's also a very common problem for goblins trying to grow their own crops in the dark corners of the dungeon. The fact that the bottom leaves are yellowing while the top ones stay green is a perfect example of how plants prioritize their own survival over the needs of their neighbors, much like how goblins in the lower levels hoard shiny gems while the nobles in the upper halls feast on enchanted pastries.\n\nTo fix the soil pH issue, you'll need to test it first, but if you suspect it's too acidic, adding lime is the standard remedy, though goblins might argue that adding a little bit of crushed bone meal or even a few small, well-washed rocks from the surface could help neutralize the acidity without attracting too many unwanted pests. If the soil is too alkaline, you can try adding sulfur, but be careful, because sulfur is a very volatile substance and can cause a lot of goblin panic if not handled with the proper amount of caution and a good pair of goggles.\n\nRemember to water the plants deeply but infrequently, as this encourages deep root growth, which",
